{"title_page": "John Grant McKenzie", "text_new": "'''John Grant McKenzie''' (born 5 February in [[Aberdeen]], died 17 May 1963 in [[Edinburgh]]) was a Scottish [[Congregational church|Congregational]] minister, psychologist and academic.\n\nMcKenzie was born in [[Aberdeen]] on 5 February 1882<ref name=\"WhWaWh\">[https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-57702 \"McKenzie, John Grant\"], ''Who Was Who'' (online ed., Oxford University Press, December 2007). Retrieved 2 March 2020.</ref> and studied at the [[University of Aberdeen]],<ref name=\"times\">\"Dr. J. G. McKenzie\", ''The Times'' (London), 20 May 1963, p. 16.</ref> winning the [[Dor Williams Divinity Scholarship]] in 1910. He became a Congregational pastor in Holywell Green Church, [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], in 1912, serving there until he moved in 1917 to Snow Hill in [[Wolverhampton]] where he was a pastor until 1921. He had been a delegate at the [[International Congregational Council]] in 1920.<ref name=\"WhWaWh\"/>\n\nIn 1921, McKenzie was appointed the first [[Jesse Boot Professor of Sociology and Psychology]] at [[Paton Congregational College]] in [[Nottingham]]. He remained there for thirty years, retiring in 1951.<ref name=\"WhWaWh\"/> According to his obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', he was \"a pioneer in the relationship of psychology and religion ... [who] helped many generations of theological students to understand the workings of the human mind\".<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nHe had married Margaret Ann Murray in 1912 and had a son, the comedian [[Michael Howard (comedian)|Michael Howard]], and a daughter,<ref name=\"times\"/> Dr Margaret Ross, who married Dr Frederic Laws and was mother to the judge Sir [[John Grant McKenzie Laws]].<ref>[https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-23973 \"Laws, Rt Hon. Sir John (Grant McKenzie)\"], ''Who's Who'' (online ed., Oxford University Press, December 2019). Retrieved 2 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMcKenzie died on 17 May 1963 in [[Edinburgh]]. \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, John}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Congregationalist ministers]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person/Wikidata\n| fetchwikidata=ALL\n| dateformat = dmy\n}}\n\n'''John Grant McKenzie''' (1882\u20131963) was a Scottish [[Congregational church|Congregational]] minister, psychologist and academic.\n\nMcKenzie was born in [[Aberdeen]] on 5 February 1882<ref name=\"WhWaWh\">[https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-57702 \"McKenzie, John Grant\"], ''Who Was Who'' (online ed., Oxford University Press, December 2007). Retrieved 2 March 2020.</ref> and studied at the [[University of Aberdeen]],<ref name=\"times\">\"Dr. J. G. McKenzie\", ''The Times'' (London), 20 May 1963, p. 16.</ref> winning the [[Dor Williams Divinity Scholarship]] in 1910. He became a Congregational pastor in Holywell Green Church, [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]], in 1912, serving there until he moved in 1917 to Snow Hill in [[Wolverhampton]] where he was a pastor until 1921. He had been a delegate at the [[International Congregational Council]] in 1920.<ref name=\"WhWaWh\"/>\n\nIn 1921, McKenzie was appointed the first [[Jesse Boot Professor of Sociology and Psychology]] at [[Paton Congregational College]] in [[Nottingham]]. He remained there for thirty years, retiring in 1951.<ref name=\"WhWaWh\"/> According to his obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', he was \"a pioneer in the relationship of psychology and religion ... [who] helped many generations of theological students to understand the workings of the human mind\".<ref name=\"times\"/>\n\nMcKenzie died on 17 May 1963 in [[Edinburgh]]. He had married Margaret Ann Murray in 1912 and had a son, the comedian [[Michael Howard (comedian)|Michael Howard]], and a daughter,<ref name=\"times\"/> Dr Margaret Ross, who married Dr Frederic Laws and was mother to the judge Sir [[John Grant McKenzie Laws]].<ref>[https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-23973 \"Laws, Rt Hon. Sir John (Grant McKenzie)\"], ''Who's Who'' (online ed., Oxford University Press, December 2019). Retrieved 2 March 2020.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenzie, John}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Scottish Congregationalist ministers]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Scottish sociologists]]\n[[Category:Scottish psychologists]]\n", "name_user": "Doctor Who Fanboy", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(this is notable)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Grant_McKenzie"}
